snippet.textDisplay: I clicked on this video to get a little more clarity. I have a 10 year old son who started getting blind when he was 5 and now he is totally blind because of Optic nerve dystrophy.  But the thing is, even before he went blind there were always problems at school where teachers would say he is a difficult child, he doesn't want to work, he doesn't want to communicate which counted against him. So when we found out that he has big problems with his eyes I thought okay, now we have the answer to why he had these problems. But He is in a Blind school now, he has been held back two years already because he is still not communicative, he cries when being asked questions, he cries when he feels overwhelmed, he gets mad out of frustration. There were times he would kick me out of unexpected aggressiveness and people just keep on telling me that he is only frustrated because he can't accept he is blind and I just feel like my words are falling on deaf ears because We have been to doctors, We took him for MRI scans for headaches and other reasons but the scans showed no other problems than the blindness. The doctors he went to diagnosed him with ADHD last year and he has been  on medications ever since. Yes I can see a difference in his school reports with the work getting little better. But his teacher called me in again last week to tell me that she also can see that he is such a smart boy, but he is working way too slow and he can't do tasks on his own. she has to keep help him to remember what to do next. And this has been the problem since he started pre school. This past week he has been crying in the car from school almost everyday because he struggles with keeping friends, he struggles with social skills, he struggles with school work, he struggles with keeping up, he can't answer his teacher because he is too scared too give a wrong answer so he rather just don't answer. He takes everything too hard on himself, he lives in his own world. When his friends are telling jokes he is the only one not laughing and I personally don't think it's because  he doesn't get the joke, he understand very well. I feel so helpless, because I can see and feel his struggle. So why do I feel that ADHD isn't the right diagnoses?

snippet.textDisplay:
Do they fit your mold of autism? Never. "How what are their opinions?" is a less artificial attraction style title for this video. But you are trying to influence people to be far right extremists.
On to the main event:
The term special isn't intended to be offensive but some bad folks use it for prejudicial motives and methods. People who are not considered "Special," with a tonality to pronouncing tend to divide their self from that term.
Making friends is a challenge for several. For me, I had a hard time knowing what friends are, and how we treat each other. I did not have friends. Thought some were my friends, but now I realize that we were in a different treatment relationship (me the bully, in essence) and later after I was in a horrific accident, I went to complete Jr. college and they said to me, "Sorry to admit we weren't friends.
I have not been diagnosed with any specific informality, like such. My time with therapists and psychologists have lately been resorting to no diagnosis directly reported to me.
Most are displeased with pity. As can be said, pity does nothing for the victim of those looking down on them. I am stuck with my parents who don't both call me baby, but mother does so and I cannot dissuade that. My actual brain damage didn't help, I am treated the same way I was previous to the crash.
I would rather people had no stigma about mental types. I act a certain way, so do you. Do you know who just got a little pas this in certain areas? The lgbtqia+ community, attention to the differences seems to first bring forward hatred for it as well as some trying to take advantage of it.
Say what is connectable between everyone? They exist as they are. If we are to specify who we connect to, and identify the quality of that connection have we not been encouraging a persisting prejudice? Yes we have. Any number of people, from many walks of life connect for better or for worse will relate in some fashion to one another. As with anyone I am in conversation with, I try to guess what they mean to say, showing that I am listening correctly.
As with this all, it seem the wisest among us is the quietest with the group. 'Twas a wonderful conclusion given before you called for a wrap-up of this event. For my personal story: I had, as well as still have, a difficult time making eye contact in person without rationalizing the reason to do so. One thing that has helped me there is that I read and researched that looking at other's eyes, any other, dog, cat, person, graphic, person, is good for your health, like looking at nature would be. I look at some friendly eyes because I hope to help them and myself live longer. Doing this for me and for you, one could look at photos of eyes on a controlled digital spectrum to get a least some bit of help.

(I have mild autism)
I don’t see the point of telling everyone you meet that you’re autistic. Like either they’ll feel sorry for you and nothing will change, or they’ll treat you differently. And the last thing a “special person” (also fyi I hate that term) like me would want is to be treated differently.
Idk. Maybe I only think that b/c I only found out I was autistic two years ago. But I don’t see any reason I would need to tell all my friends that I’ve known for years that I’m autistic.

snippet.textDisplay: As someone with autism, my opinion is that I would never change who I am. Autism is my identity, and it is not a disability to me, it's just a different ability. It's not a lack of ability, it's a lack of solution. I feel proud to be in a community with people who experience the same things as me. Autism is not all bad, it can make you see the world in a whole different way, it can amplify your talents, and it makes you stronger and more accepting towards yourself. Next month is autism awareness month, much love to all my fellow autistic people out there. We can do this. :)

snippet.textDisplay: I think the question about pity is an interesting one. As another autistic person who has other mental and physical health issues, my answer would be “I appreciate concern or wanting to help, but to me “pity” just makes me think of someone babying me or looking down on me and going “what a shame.” If that makes sense. It usually has good intentions, but it makes me uncomfortable.”

snippet.textDisplay: I've always wondered how someone with autism can deal with everyday life in a rural area like the south.  It may be more accepting in cities, where people are better educated about it and its well understood, but in the south I can only imagine what's its like.  People are very judgemental here, and only want others to see things their way (I.e. Christian).  I can attest to this, as when I was still a child I used to be this way (judgemental) and to some extent maybe I still am and don't know it as I'm simply not aware.  But even now, I see adults everyday here act like judgemental children throwing insults and see it in their actions, especially with Trump in office.  If anyone feels like sharing and has experience with this, feel free to leave a comment below.  If I've offended anyone by writing this, I apologize.  Its just how I feel things are here in the south.  And I've lived here for almost 30 years practically my whole life.
